{"type":"message","id":"ffadfca3","parentId":"da1e30b9","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:07:32.643Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so C:\\Windows is 24.9GB (not counting WinSxS, etc.), Downloads is only 0.2GB, Documents is negligible.\n\nLet me now try to find the actual largest directories using a faster method. The problem is these scans take forever. Let me try to find the top-level directories at the C:\\ level excluding the Windows directory.\n\nActually, wait - I realize I should check what the disk full picture looks like. C: has 444.7GB used and 30GB free. The user profile (C:\\Users\\Zwmar) we've measured at roughly:\n- AppData\\Roaming: 32.17GB\n\n\n- AppData\\Local\\Programs: 9.38GB\n- AppData\\Local\\Temp: 2.8GB\n- AppData\\Local\\JetBrains: 0.42GB\n- .openclaw: 0.07GB\n- Claw: 0.01GB\n- dev: 0.16GB\n\nThat's about 45GB total. Downloads and Documents are negligible. So where's the rest of the 445GB? The Windows directory is 24.9GB, and then there's the Windows\\WinSxS folder and other system directories that could account for the difference.\n\nI should check if there are any mounted VHDs, OneDrive sync folders, or other hidden drives that might be taking up space. But more likely, I'm just missing some obvious large directories. Let me do a more systematic scan at the root level of C: to find what's actually consuming most of the disk.","thinkingSignature":"e3d5ddf8d48246519235c30dfe86143b3f56d6fe57945497519a047014b9683b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_roywcx0aq902_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem C:\\ -Directory -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object {\n    try {\n        $size = (Get-ChildItem $_.FullName -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Measure-Object Length -Sum).Sum\n        [PSCustomObject]@{Name=$_.Name; SizeGB=[math]::Round($size/1GB,1)}\n    } catch {}\n} | Sort-Object SizeGB -Descending | Select-Object -First 15 | Format-Table -AutoSize","timeout":60}}],"api"